@article{darrowFDAApprovalRegulation2020,
  title = {{{FDA Approval}} and {{Regulation}} of {{Pharmaceuticals}}, 1983-2018},
  author = {Darrow, Jonathan J. and Avorn, Jerry and Kesselheim, Aaron S.},
  year = 2020,
  journal = {JAMA},
  doi = {10.1001/jama.2019.20288},
  urldate = {2026-03-08},
  keywords = {FDA,MUST_CITE},
  note = {Paper: Darrow, Jonathan J.; Avorn, Jerry; Kesselheim, Aaron S. (2020)
\par
Title: "FDA Approval and Regulation of Pharmaceuticals, 1983--2018"
\par
Journal: JAMA
\par
1. Research Question:
\par
How has the U.S. FDA drug approval system evolved from 1983 to 2018 with respect to regulatory policies, approval pathways, and the number and types of drugs approved? The paper examines how legislation, regulatory reforms, and expedited programs have shaped the speed, structure, and incentives of pharmaceutical approval in the United States.
\par
2. Data:
\par
The paper compiles multiple FDA administrative and regulatory datasets, including:
\par
- FDA approvals of new drugs (1984--2018)
\par
- Biologic approvals (1984--2018)
\par
- Generic drug approvals (1970--2018)
\par
- Vaccine approvals (1998--2018)
\par
Regulatory pathway and program data:
\par
- Orphan Drug designations (1984--2018)
\par
- Fast Track designations (1988--2018)
\par
- Priority Review designations (1984--2018)
\par
- Accelerated Approval pathway (1992--2018)
\par
- Breakthrough Therapy designations (2012--2018)
\par
Other information includes:
\par
- Federal legislation affecting drug regulation
\par
- FDA funding data (especially Prescription Drug User Fee Act programs)
\par
- Expanded access programs
\par
- REMS requirements
\par
The sources primarily include FDA databases, federal statutes, and regulatory reports.
\par
3. Identification:
\par
The paper does not use a causal identification strategy. It is a descriptive institutional analysis. The authors analyze trends in drug approvals and regulatory programs over time using descriptive statistics, policy timelines, and counts of approvals. Changes in approval patterns are discussed in relation to major legislative reforms such as the Hatch-Waxman Act (1984), the Prescription Drug User Fee Act (1992), and the FDA Safety and Innovation Act (2012), but no formal causal inference is attempted.
\par
4. Main Results:
\par
Several major trends emerge from the analysis.
\par
Drug approvals fluctuated but increased again in the 2010s:
\par
Average annual approvals were about 34 in the 1990s, fell to around 25 in the 2000s, and increased to about 41 in the 2010--2018 period.
\par
Biologic drugs became a larger share of approvals:
\par
Median biologic approvals rose from about 2.5 per year in the 1990s to roughly 12 per year in the 2014--2018 period.
\par
Expedited approval programs expanded substantially:
\par
Programs designed to accelerate drug development and review --- including Fast Track, Priority Review, Accelerated Approval, and Breakthrough Therapy designation --- have become increasingly common and central to the regulatory system.
\par
FDA funding increasingly relies on industry user fees:
\par
The Prescription Drug User Fee Act significantly increased FDA resources but also introduced review deadlines and greater interaction between regulators and pharmaceutical companies.
\par
Generic drug approvals increased dramatically:
\par
Following the Hatch-Waxman Act and later generic drug user fee legislation, generic approvals rose substantially, dramatically expanding the supply of generic pharmaceuticals in the U.S. market.
\par
5. Limitations:
\par
The study is descriptive and does not provide causal estimates of the effects of regulatory reforms on approval speed or drug outcomes. It does not analyze postmarketing safety outcomes, drug misuse, or diversion into illicit markets. The paper also does not examine firm behavior, pricing dynamics, or prescribing behavior, and therefore cannot directly assess downstream health or market consequences of regulatory changes.
\par
6. How this connects to MY project:
\par
This paper provides the institutional background for understanding regulatory acceleration in the U.S. pharmaceutical system. It documents the expansion of expedited approval pathways and the increasing importance of programs designed to speed drug development and regulatory review. For a project studying whether faster regulatory approval may increase diversion risk in drug markets, this paper helps establish that regulatory acceleration is a real and growing feature of the FDA system. It also shows how regulatory reforms such as PDUFA and expedited approval programs increased the speed and volume of drug approvals, which may increase legal drug supply and potentially create new pathways for misuse or diversion into illicit markets. The paper therefore provides critical context for analyzing how regulatory policy changes may generate downstream consequences beyond the intended goal of faster patient access to new drugs.},
  file = {/Users/alexdelatorre/Zotero/storage/Q7B86FGQ/Darrow et al. - 2020 - FDA Approval and Regulation of Pharmaceuticals, 1983-2018.pdf}
}

